ten a filled or hollow sphere, can extend the lifetime of encapsulated biomedical modalities in circulation and in target tissue. However, there is a great need to improve the drug loading and targeting efficiency of these particles. Recently, several simulations and in vitro experimental studies reported that particle shape plays a pivotal role in the targeted delivery of molecules. To better understand these findings and subsequently expedite the use of particles in biomedical applications, this review paper summarizes the methods to prepare non-spherical nano- and micro-scaled particles. In addition, this review covers studies reporting the effects of particle shape on the loading, delivery, and release of encapsulated bioactive cargos. Finally, it discusses future directions to further improve the properties of non-spherical particles.</ce:para></abstract></dc:description><link href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/abstract/scopus_id/84919360495" rel="self"/><link href="http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&amp;scp=84919360495&amp;origin=inward" rel="scopus"/><link href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/search/scopus?query=refeid%282-s2.0-84919360495%29" rel="cited-by"/></coredata><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60073750" id="60073750"><affilname>Korea Institute of Industrial Technology Evaluation and Planning</affilname></affiliation><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60000745" id="60000745"><affilname>University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign</affilname></affiliation><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60014156" id="60014156"><affilname>Soongsil University</affilname></affiliation><authors><author auid="56452324100" seq="1"><ce:initials>J.</ce:initials><ce:indexed-name>Chen J.</ce:indexed-name><ce:surname>Chen</ce:surname><ce:given-name>Jinrong</ce:given-name><preferred-name><ce:initials>J.</ce:initials><ce:ind